[2026-05-28 23:19:04] local.INFO: Recommendation Step Output {"recommendation":{"confidence":0.9,"customer_explanation":"You have a water leak happening right under your kitchen or bathroom sink. This means water is escaping from one of the pipes, connections, or parts of the faucet assembly there. If this leak is not fixed promptly, it can cause significant damage to your cabinet, the floor underneath, and could even lead to unhealthy mold growth in your home.","diy_checks":["Carefully look under the sink with a flashlight to pinpoint the exact spot where the water is coming from. Check all visible pipes, connections, and the base of the faucet.","Feel for any dampness or moisture on the pipes and connections, especially around the joints where pipes connect.","If you notice a slightly loose nut on a connection, you can try gently tightening it with an adjustable wrench. Be careful not to overtighten, as this could cause more damage.","Try to determine if the leak is from the faucet itself, the drain pipes directly below the sink, or the water supply lines connecting to the faucet."],"estimated_price_max":3000,"estimated_price_min":1500,"immediate_actions":["Immediately place a bucket or a large container directly under the leak to catch all the dripping water and prevent further damage to your cabinet and floor.","Use old cloths or towels to soak up any water that has already spilled inside the cabinet.","If the leak is steady or significant, locate the small shut-off valves usually found directly under the sink (one for hot, one for cold) and turn them clockwise until the water stops. If you can't find these, you may need to turn off the main water supply to your entire house, usually found near your water meter outside."],"issue_type":"pipe_leak","likely_cause":"Most likely, this leak is happening because one of the pipe connections has become loose over time, a rubber seal or washer inside a fitting has worn out, or a section of the pipe itself has started to corrode (rust) and developed a small hole. Sometimes, the sealant around the sink drain or the faucet base can also fail.","preventive_maintenance":["Every few months, take a quick look under your sinks in the kitchen and bathrooms for any early signs of dampness, water stains, or small drips.","Avoid using very harsh chemical drain cleaners regularly, as they can sometimes damage the inside of your pipes over time.","Ensure that any new plumbing fixtures or pipes are installed correctly by a skilled person to prevent future leaks from loose connections."],"professional_steps":["A professional plumber will accurately find the exact source of the leak, even if it's hidden or very small, using their experience and tools.","They will then either tighten loose connections, replace worn-out washers, seals, or O-rings, or carefully cut out and replace the corroded or damaged section of the pipe. Sometimes, an entire fitting or part of the drain assembly might need replacement.","After the repair, they will thoroughly test the system to ensure there are no more leaks and that everything is working correctly."],"recommended_service":"It is highly recommended to call a reliable and licensed plumber for 'leak detection and pipe repair'. They can accurately find the source of the leak and fix it properly to ensure it doesn't happen again soon.","required_tools":["Bucket","Old cloths/towels","Flashlight","Adjustable wrench","Screwdriver (if you need to remove cabinet panels)"],"risk_level":"medium","safety_precautions":["Always shut off the water supply to the sink or the entire house before you attempt any inspection or tightening of pipes to avoid getting soaked or making the leak worse.","Never try to disassemble pipes that are currently under high water pressure.","If the leak seems difficult to reach, the pipe looks heavily rusted, or you are unsure about what you are doing, it's best not to attempt a DIY fix. Call a professional plumber immediately.","Do not use excessive force when tightening connections, as this can strip the threads of the pipe or crack plastic pipes, leading to a bigger problem."],"summary":"You have a water leak under your sink, which needs to be addressed with medium urgency to prevent further water damage and potential mold growth. This is commonly caused by loose fittings, worn-out internal parts, or corroded pipes. You should take immediate steps like catching the water and turning off the supply. While some simple checks can be done by you, it's best to call a professional plumber for proper leak detection and repair to ensure a lasting solution.","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash"}} 
